480":"1424–1480","1425–1510":"1425–1510","1506 or 1510":"1506","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1522":"1522","1510":"1510","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1539":"1539","1506":"1506","Colyton, Devonshire, England":"Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Strengeston, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","St Columb Major, Cornwall, England":"St Columb Major, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Saint Columb, , Cornwall, England":"St Columb Major, Cornwall, England"},"nl":{"1462–1506 or 1510":"1462–1506","1450–1522":"1450–1522","1462–1506":"1462–1506","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1424–1480":"1424–1480","1425–1510":"1425–1510","1506 or 1510":"1506","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1522":"1522","1510":"1510","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1539":"1539","1506":"1506","Colyton, Devonshire, England":"Colyton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Strengeston, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","St Columb Major, Cornwall, England":"St Columb Major, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saint Columb, , Cornwall, England":"St Columb Major, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1462–1506 or 1510":"1462–1506","1450–1522":"1450–1522","1462–1506":"1462–1506","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1424–1480":"1424–1480","1425–1510":"1425–1510","1506 or 1510":"1506","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1522":"1522","1510":"1510","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1539":"1539","1506":"1506","Colyton, Devonshire, England":"Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Strengeston, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","St Columb Major, Cornwall, England":"St Columb Major, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Saint Columb, , Cornwall, England":"St Columb Major, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mitchell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the vernacular pronunciation in Middle English and Older Scots of the personal name   Michael  . See   Michelson  .","English and Scottish: nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>michel</i>, <i>mechel</i>, <i>muchel</i> ‘big’.","Irish (County Connacht): surname adopted as equivalent of   Mulvihill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Michell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Etienne, Yvrose.","English (Cornwall): variant of   Mitchell   and   Michel  .","German: variant of   Michel  . This surname is rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Mutch","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire) and English (Lancashire and Cheshire): nickname for a large (tall or fat) person, from Middle English <i>moche</i>, <i>muche</i> ‘big’ (a shortened form of <i>mochel</i>, <i>muchel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Muckle  ."]},{"name":"Meikle","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Middle Scots <i>mekill</i>, <i>meikill</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell   2,   Muckle  , and   Mutch  ."]},{"name":"Mickle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Mutch  .","Americanized form of German   Mickel   1 or of a homonymous Germanized Sorbian surname (see   Mickel   2)."]},{"name":"Michael","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Jewish, and Greek: from the personal name <i>Michael</i>, ultimately from Hebrew <i>Mika’el</i> ‘Who is like God?’. This was borne by an archangel in the Bible, the protector of Israel (Daniel 10:13, 12:1; Rev. 12:7). In Christian tradition, Michael was regarded as the warrior archangel, conqueror of Satan, and the personal name was correspondingly popular throughout Europe, especially in knightly and military families. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Mihály</b> (see   Mihaly  ), Czech and Slovak   Michal  , Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Mikhael   and   Mikhail  , and also patronymics and other derivatives from these names, e.g. Greek   Papamichael  , its cognate <b>Papamichalis</b>, and   Michaelides  , Serbian <b>Mihajlović</b> (see   Mihajlovic  ), and Slovenian <b>Mihelčič</b> (see   Mihelcic  ). Compare   Mikeal  ."]},{"name":"Mitchel","meanings":["English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Mixell","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Muckle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’ (Old English <i>mycel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle   and   Mutch  .","South German: from a diminutive of   Muck   ‘gnat’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Mitchell was born in 1462, in St Columb Major, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Mitchell III, was 38 and his mother, Sarah Anne Whitford, was 37. He had at least 1 son with Lady Margaret Cromwell. He died in 1506, in Somerset, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1462–1506 or 1510":"1462–1506","1450–1522":"1450–1522","1462–1506":"1462–1506","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1424–1480":"1424–1480","1425–1510":"1425–1510","1506 or 1510":"1506","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1522":"